      "content": "If your manual counters don't catch it, you need to introduce a \"leak trace\" mechanism that marks allocations with unique, non-intrusive identifiers. Since you cannot use heavy tools, you can create a lightweight `AllocationTag` struct that stores a unique ID and a pointer to the source file and line number in a global map. Every time you `new` or `malloc` in any module, you attach this tag. When you `delete` or `free`, you remove the tag.\n\nTo isolate the module without crashing the system, you should implement a \"slow-cycle audit\" function that runs once every 10,000 cycles (roughly every few seconds). This function iterates through your global map, checks for any remaining tags, and prints a summary of which file/line count the highest. This approach is CPU-efficient because it only runs periodically and doesn't interfere with real-time CAN bus handling.\n\nHere is a simple pattern to implement this:\n\n```cpp\n// Global map to track leaks\nstd::map<int, std::pair<const char*, int>> leak_tracker;\n\nstruct AllocationTag {\n    int id;\n    const char* file;\n    int line;",
